            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How Illinois sales tax works</h2>
              <p>
                Illinois sales tax is a combination of the statewide
                <strong>Retailers’ Occupation Tax</strong> (state rate) plus a
                patchwork of <strong>local add‑on taxes</strong> imposed by
                counties, municipalities, transit districts, and other special
                districts.
              </p>
              <p>
                The calculator on this page is designed for quick estimates. It
                is not a substitute for the official rate tables and bulletins
                published by the Illinois Department of Revenue (IDOR).
              </p>

              <h3>Basic formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Sales tax</strong> = Purchase price × (Total tax rate
                  ÷ 100)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Total price</strong> = Purchase price + Sales tax</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you already have a tax‑inclusive price and want to back out
                the tax portion, use:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Taxable price</strong> = Total price ÷ (1 + Total tax
                  rate ÷ 100)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Sales tax</strong> = Total price − Taxable price</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Components of Illinois sales tax</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>State rate:</strong> Illinois imposes a base state
                  rate (commonly 6.25%) on most taxable sales.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>County and city rates:</strong> Counties and
                  municipalities can add local sales taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Special district taxes:</strong> Transit, mass
                  transit, and other districts may add additional percentages.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Home‑rule taxes:</strong> Some cities (including
                  Chicago) can impose their own home‑rule sales taxes.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The combined rate you pay at the register is the sum of all
                applicable components at the location where the sale is sourced
                (often the store location or the destination for shipped goods).
              </p>

              <h2>Using the Illinois sales tax calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>purchase amount</strong> before tax (or the
                  total amount if you choose “back out tax”).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Select a <strong>location</strong> from the dropdown, or
                  choose “Enter custom combined rate”.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you choose custom, type the
                  <strong>combined rate</strong> (state + all local taxes) as a
                  percentage, for example <code>8.75</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose whether you want to <strong>add tax</strong> to a
                  pre‑tax price or <strong>back out tax</strong> from a
                  tax‑inclusive price.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate</strong> to see the breakdown of
                  state, local, and total tax.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example: Chicago purchase</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you buy $250 of taxable goods in Chicago. Using an
                illustrative combined rate of 9.25%:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>State portion (6.25%): $250 × 0.0625 = $15.63</li>
                <li>Local portion (3.00%): $250 × 0.03 = $7.50</li>
                <li>Total sales tax: $23.13</li>
                <li>Total price: $273.13</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Important notes and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rates change frequently.</strong> Local governments
                  can adopt new taxes or change rates during the year. Always
                  confirm with IDOR’s official publications or a certified tax
                  professional before filing or charging tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Different products, different rules.</strong>
                  Groceries, prepared food, prescription drugs, vehicles, and
                  certain services may be taxed at different rates or under
                  different rules than general merchandise.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Origin vs. destination sourcing.</strong> Illinois
                  sourcing rules can differ for in‑store vs. shipped sales and
                  for remote sellers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>This tool is for estimation only.</strong> It does not
                  file returns, determine nexus, or replace professional advice.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
